text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: The Singer's Formant%0a:Author: ZoeC%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 25.04.2021 - 19:09%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-220804-948020#%0a* [-05.05.2021 - 15:08-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-220804-948020#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow are opera singers able to be heard over an orchestra?%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aMany empirical and observational studies have been conducted in reference to the dilemma of the classical singer’s challenge to be heard over the full orchestra. For instance, a soprano has a fundamental frequency (frequency of vocal folds alone before going through the articulators) of around 250-1500 Hz, which is much quieter than an average orchestra. However, she can still be heard by the audience by manipulating her articulators, embouchure, and breath support in a way that creates harmonics, or overtones, which are basically integer multiples of the fundamental frequency. In fact, this is actually a very natural process. A baby’s cry is evolutionarily built to be so piercing that it cuts through all other sounds; babies have a small larynx, allowing higher harmonics to form easily. In turn, opera singers today can imitate this by narrowing the larynx to create higher layers of frequency.%0a%0a In other words, the singer makes the harmonic series work in their benefit; this is a linear combination of pure tones by the formula [fundamental analysis frequency (f) + integer multiples (2f,3f,4f)]. The technical term for this process in acoustic physics and linguistics is called the singer’s formant. By voice teachers in the opera world, this goes by the name of “squillo”, the Italian word for “ring”. %0a%0aThe word formant refers to dominant harmonic overtones in a certain phonation that can be visualized on a spectrogram. Formants can be used in acoustic phonetics to determine the quality of a vowel by showing patterns of voicing of different frequencies present in the phonation. It can also be used to determine consonants by showing patterns of frication in different areas. In terms of the singer’s formant, a spectrogram will show the fundamental frequency (in the music world, pitch) of the note and a presence of an additional formant (or sometimes two!) on the next pitches of the harmonic series, layered in octaves above the pitch. Use of the singer’s formant helps the voice to cut through a theatre, instead of straining to project louder than the orchestra in a literal sense. %0a%0ahttps://www.actorproject.org/tor/timbre-lingo/2019/12/10/the-singers-formant%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a:Category: Varia%0a:Essential: {Category.Varia$:essential}%0a:Title: The Singers Formant%0a:Author: ZoeC%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 25.04.2021 - 19:13%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow are opera singers able to be heard over an orchestra?%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aMany empirical and observational studies have been conducted in reference to the dilemma of the classical singer’s challenge to be heard over the full orchestra. For instance, a soprano has a fundamental frequency (frequency of vocal folds alone before going through the articulators) of around 250-1500 Hz, which is much quieter than an average orchestra. However, she can still be heard by the audience by manipulating her articulators, embouchure, and breath support in a way that creates harmonics, or overtones, which are basically integer multiples of the fundamental frequency. In fact, this is actually a very natural process. A baby’s cry is evolutionarily built to be so piercing that it cuts through all other sounds; babies have a small larynx, allowing higher harmonics to form easily. In turn, opera singers today can imitate this by narrowing the larynx to create higher layers of frequency.%0a %0aIn other words, the singer makes the harmonic series work in their benefit; this is a linear combination of pure tones by the formula [fundamental analysis frequency (f) + integer multiples (2f,3f,4f)]. The technical term for this process in acoustic physics and linguistics is called the singer’s formant. By voice teachers in the opera world, this goes by the name of “squillo”, the Italian word for “ring”. %0a%0aThe word formant refers to dominant harmonic overtones in a certain phonation that can be visualized on a spectrogram. Formants can be used in acoustic phonetics to determine the quality of a vowel by showing patterns of voicing of different frequencies present in the phonation. It can also be used to determine consonants by showing patterns of frication in different areas. In terms of the singer’s formant, a spectrogram will show the fundamental frequency (in the music world, pitch) of the note and a presence of an additional formant (or sometimes two!) on the next pitches of the harmonic series, layered in octaves above the pitch. Use of the singer’s formant helps the voice to cut through a theatre, instead of straining to project louder than the orchestra in a literal sense. %0a%0ahttps://www.actorproject.org/tor/timbre-lingo/2019/12/10/the-singers-formant%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
