before going through the articulators) of around 250-1500 Hz, which is much quieter than an average orchestra. However, she can still be heard by the audience by manipulating her articulators, embouchure, and breath support in a way that creates harmonics, or overtones, which are basically integer multiples of the fundamental frequency. In fact, this is actually a very natural process. A baby’s cry is evolutionarily built to be so piercing that it cuts through all other sounds; babies have a small larynx, allowing higher harmonics to form easily. In turn, opera singers today can imitate this by narrowing the larynx to create higher layers of frequency.%0a%3c  %0a%3c In other words, the singer makes the harmonic series work in their benefit; this is a linear combination of pure tones by the formula [fundamental analysis frequency (f) + integer multiples (2f,3f,4f)]. The technical term for this process in acoustic physics and linguistics is called the singer’s formant. By voice teachers in the opera world, this goes by the name of “squillo”, the Italian word for “ring”. %0a
